The Supreme Court's doctrine of broad presidential immunity would have astonished the founders. They rejected the principle that the king can do no wrong. They did not resurrect it in republican form—yet the Court has done precisely that, clothing royal prerogative in constitutional language.

If official purpose immunizes official crime, then law constrains only the powerless. That is not rule of law. It is rule by law—a weapon wielded downward.

The same Court that invokes original meaning to constrain agencies shows no comparable urgency when the executive defies Congress or disregards the judiciary itself. Doctrine bends predictably toward power. This is not jurisprudence. It is partisanship with citations.

𝗧𝗼 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗔𝗺𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗣𝗲𝗼𝗽𝗹𝗲

I do not address this primarily to you, Mr. President. Power does not reform itself. I address it to the American people.

You remain sovereign. Every official is your servant. They possess only the authority you permit—authority you can reclaim.

But sovereignty unexercised is sovereignty forfeited. Those who applaud overreach because they favor the officeholder will suffer when the office changes hands. Those who accept surveillance because they have nothing to hide will discover that privacy was the foundation of every freedom they thought they possessed.

Washington warned that the Constitution could survive foreign enemies but might not survive domestic indifference—citizens who preferred comfort to vigilance, faction to principle, victory to liberty.

He was right to worry.

𝗖𝗼𝗻𝗰𝗹𝘂𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻

I do not call for revolution. I call for enforcement of a Constitution that already exists.

A Congress that legislates and checks. Courts that place law above power. A president who honors his oath instead of probing its limits.
Washington surrendered power he could have kept forever. The founders risked their lives, fortunes, and sacred honor. I ask Americans to risk only discomfort—the discomfort of holding their own side accountable, of applying principles when application is inconvenient, of treating the Constitution as binding law rather than campaign slogan.
If that is too much, we do not deserve what they built.

The accounts of liberty are past due. The only question is whether we pay—or default.

Jeffrey Wernick
